(3pts) We could create a bar plot of day_of_week using the standard approach with ggplot() + geom_bar(); however, with large datasets like this one, it can take a small amount of time to do the calculations necessary to create the bar chart. This is because geom_bar() tabulates the counts in each category when the line of code is run. For large datasets, it’s better to store the counts ahead of time and then reference these when creating the bar plot, as we did in Lab2 with duration_marginal.

Here, create a bar plot showing the distribution of day_of_week (at the count scale), but calculate the marginal distribution ahead of time (i.e., use an approach similar to Lab2, but on the count scale instead of the percentage scale).

Here is our code for the bar plot:

#compute the marginal distribution
day_counts <- mateys_movies %>%
  group_by(day_of_week) %>%
  summarize(count = n())
#now make the plot
ggplot(day_counts, aes(x = day_of_week, y = count)) +

  labs(title = "Number of Matey's Film Ratings by Day of Week",
       x = "Day of Week", y = "Number of Movie Ratings") +

Compare the above code to the code you wrote in Part C. Answer the following questions:

  • Why do we use stat = "identity" in the above code?

We use stat = "identity" when counts are already calculated; the count variable is assigned to the y-axis aesthetic, and identity will use that variable to draw the bars of the bar chart at the appropriate/corresponding heights.

  • What is the default stat in geom_bar() (i.e., what is used by default in Part C)?

stat = "count" is the default, which takes the full dataset and counts the number of observations in each category of the variable assigned to the x-aesthetic (in this case, day_of_week).

I again prefer the graph in Part D; although it’s more difficult to assess the marginal distribution of popular (compared to the marginal distribution of day_of_week), by comparing the total blue color to the total red color, we can still see that about one-third of movies were considered “Popular,” whereas the other two-thirds of movies were considered “Not Popular.” I found it a bit easier to add these colors than the colors in the Part E plot.   • The conditional distribution of popular given day_of_week.

I definitely prefer the graph in Part F; as I put in the title, this conditional distribution is exactly what that graph is displaying - i.e., we can easily see what the proportion of popular is for any given day. We can see that the proportion of “Popular” movies is around 25% for Tuesdays, Wednesdays, Fridays, and Sundays; meanwhile, the proportion is around 40-45% for Mondays, Thursdays, and Saturdays.

  • The conditional distribution of day_of_week given popular.

I prefer the graph in Part E; by focusing on just the red bars or just the blue bars, I can easily see what the conditional distribution is for day_of_week given either value of popular. In terms of most and least common days, the conditional distribution for either value of popular seems pretty simiar: Saturday-Monday are the most frequent, and Tuesday-Friday are less frequent.   1. (5pts) Now, write out (in numbers) the conditional distribution of day_of_week given popular, i.e., the distribution of day_of_week for each value of popular. In your answer, please include the code you used to figure this out. A few hints for this question:
  • If I asked you to write out the marginal distribution of day_of_week, you would report back 7 proportions that add up to 1 (corresponding to the estimated probabilities of a movie rating being on each day of the week).
  • The conditional distribution I’m asking for is a function of popular, which is a binary variable. In other words, your answer should communicate something like, “If a movie is popular, then the distribution of day_of_week is” followed by 7 proportions that add up to 1. Similarly, you should communicate what the proportions are when the movie is not popular. (Thus, your final answer should have 2 sets of 7 proportions; you only need to include these 2 sets of 7 proportions in your answer.)
  • The subset() function might be helpful here; this function takes in a dataset and returns the subset of the dataset that fulfills certain criteria (e.g., a dataset only containing movies that are popular). See the help documentation for this function for details. Alternatively, you can also use the prop.table() function.

One efficient way to answer this question is to use the prop.table() function:

prop.table(table(mateys_movies$popular, mateys_movies$day_of_week), margin = 1)
##              
##                   Friday     Monday   Saturday     Sunday   Thursday    Tuesday
##   Not Popular 0.08939709 0.20374220 0.13929314 0.26819127 0.08523909 0.10810811
##   Popular     0.06250000 0.25781250 0.22656250 0.17578125 0.15234375 0.07031250
##              
##                Wednesday
##   Not Popular 0.10602911
##   Popular     0.05468750

By setting margin = 1, we see that the top row displays the condititional distribution of day_of_week given “Not Popular”, and the bottom row does the same for “Popular.” We know these are indeed the conditional distributions in part because the proportions add up to 1 in each row.

Alternatively, we could compare these vectors manually, using the following code:

#subset of the data with popular movies
popularData = subset(mateys_movies, popular == "Popular")
#subset of the data with unpopular movies
unpopularData = subset(mateys_movies, popular == "Not Popular")

#distribution of day_of_week
#conditional on Popular
table(popularData$day_of_week)/nrow(popularData)
## 
##    Friday    Monday  Saturday    Sunday  Thursday   Tuesday Wednesday 
## 0.0625000 0.2578125 0.2265625 0.1757812 0.1523438 0.0703125 0.0546875
#distribution of day_of_week
#conditional on Not Popular
table(unpopularData$day_of_week)/nrow(unpopularData)
## 
##     Friday     Monday   Saturday     Sunday   Thursday    Tuesday  Wednesday 
## 0.08939709 0.20374220 0.13929314 0.26819127 0.08523909 0.10810811 0.10602911

The above code computes what the estimated probability of each day given popular (i.e., the conditional distribution). As stated in the comments of the code, the first set of seven numbers corresponds to the conditional distribution of day_of_week given that a movie is “Popular;” likewise, the second set of seven numbers corresponds to the conditional distribution of day_of_week given that a movie is “Not Popular.” From this alone we can’t see if there is a statistically significant difference between these two sets of numbers, but we can at least observe that (as we’ve commented previously), across both values of popular, Saturday-Monday are the most frequent, and Tuesday-Friday are less frequent.

  1. (2pts) Now we’re going to recreate the mosaic plot on the Wikipedia page for mosaic plots (which Professor Branson also made in class). This plot involves decades, rather than individual years. In other words, we need to categorize the YEAR variable into decades.

The YEAR variable denotes individual years (e.g., 1955, 2006, etc.) Thus, it is a quantitative variable. However, if you type class(songs$YEAR) in the Console, you should find that R has classified this variable as a "factor" or "character" (which is not the typical class for a quantitative variable). Why has R given YEAR this unintuitive class?

(Hint: In the Console, inspecting the YEAR variable should give you an idea of what’s happening.)

If you look at the YEAR variable, you’ll find that some years are written with commas (e.g., “1,956”) and others are written without commas (e.g., “1956”). Numbers aren’t written with commas in R, and as a result, R treats instances like “1,956” as words, meaning that R treats YEAR as a categorical variable.

To further understand this, we can look at all the levels of YEAR:

After you’ve done this, answer the following questions:

  • Does it seem like any given song in this dataset is equally likely to come from each decade? (Here, 1910-1950s is considered “one” decade.) Answer this question using a statistical test.

This question is essentially asking if the song proportions are equal across decades; this is exactly what the chi-squared test assesses. Here we run the chi-squared test on the decade variable:

chisq.test(table(songs$decade))
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  table(songs$decade)
## X-squared = 181, df = 5, p-value < 2.2e-16

We see that the p-value is quite small (and certainly less than 0.05); thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the proportions are equal across decades, in favor of the alternative that they differ. In other words, we conclude that any given song in this dataset is not equally likely to come from each decade.

  1. (4pts) Professor D. Che comes up to you and makes two claims:
  • There is an equal proportion of songs from each theme on this list.
  • The decade of a song is independent of the theme of the song.

State whether you agree or disagree with each of these claims using statistical evidence. Please provide any code you used to run statistical tests.

To assess if the proportions across themes are equal, we can run a chi-square test:

chisq.test(table(songs$THEME))
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  table(songs$THEME)
## X-squared = 4.7183, df = 6, p-value = 0.5804

From this, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the proportions are equal, and thus we don’t disagree (i.e., for all practical purposes, agree) with Professor Che’s first claim.

Meanwhile, to assess if decade and THEME are independent, we can run a chi-square test for independence:

chisq.test(table(songs$decade, songs$THEME))
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(songs$decade, songs$THEME)
## X-squared = 143.21, df = 30, p-value < 2.2e-16

From this, we reject the null hypothesis that the decade and theme are independent; thus, we disagree with Professor Che’s second claim.

  1. (4pts) Looking at one of your mosaic plots in Part D, Professor Che says, “It looks like songs before the 70s are more or less the same, and songs after the 70s are more or less the same, in terms of those songs’ themes.” We’ll assess this claim in this question.

Use the following code to create two subsets of the data, pre70sSongs and post70sSongs. #which songs are before the 70s?
pre70sIndex = which(songs$decade == "1910s-50s" | songs$decade == "1960s")
#which songs are after the 70s?
post70sIndex = which(songs$decade == "1980s" | songs$decade == "1990s" | songs$decade == "2000s")
#songs before the 70s
pre70sSongs = songs[pre70sIndex,]
#songs after the 70s
post70sSongs = songs[post70sIndex,]
#get rid of empty levels

post70sSongs$decade = droplevels(post70sSongs$decade)

    shade = TRUE, las = 1)

From the first plot (using the pre-70s data), it appears that there are significantly more “people and places” songs than we would expect under the null hypothesis of independence, thereby suggesting that we should reject this null hypothesis (i.e., we would conclude that decade and THEME are not independent within the pre-70s data). Meanwhile, the second plot (using the post-70s data) does not indicate any substantially large Pearson residuals, thereby not providing any evidence to reject the null hypothesis of independence between decade and THEME for this dataset.

  1. (4pts) For the pre70sSongs and post70sSongs datasets in the previous part, run a chi-square test for independence between decade and THEME. (Don’t worry about any warnings you may get from these tests.) Interpret the results of each test in 1-2 sentences.

Here are the chi-square tests for the pre-70s and post-70s datasets:

#pre-70s test
chisq.test(table(pre70sSongs$decade, pre70sSongs$THEME))

  1. (4pts) Part F should have your interpretations for the mosaic plots, and Part G should have your interpretation for the chi-square tests. Do any of your interpretations contradict each other? If not, just say, “Nope, they don’t contradict each other.” If they do, write a 1-3 sentence explanation why the interpretations for the graphs and for the tests seem at odds with each other.

The conclusion from the mosaic plot and the chi-square test seem at odds with each other for the post-70s data; the chi-square test suggests that we should reject the null hypothesis of independence, but the plot did not provide us with any evidence to reject the same hypothesis. There are two reasons for this. First, even though the cells in the mosaic plot are all white (meaning they are between 0 and 2), some of them might be quite close to 2, but this cannot be ascertained from the color scale of the plot; indeed, this is the case for many of the residuals, as we can see below:

residuals(chisq.test(table(post70sSongs$decade, post70sSongs$THEME)))
##        
##         Heartbreak Life and death       Love Party songs People and places
##   1980s -1.2760811     -1.6797471 -0.6319976   0.8808838         1.2736435

##   1990s           -1.9200130  0.8983469
##   2000s            0.3596486 -1.0891898

The second and more important reason is that the chi-square test is a global test; i.e., it averages across the cells in the mosaic plot. From the mosaic plot, we can see that there is a general linear trend (the “higher than average” residuals are in the bottom left and top right), and once these are averaged across cells, that indicates large enough deviances from what we would expect under the null hypothesis to reject it. This is analogous to the phenomenon where all individual confidence intervals may have substantial overlap but a global F-test still rejects the null hypothesis that the group means are the same.

  1. (12 points) Consider the following types of graphs:
  • A side-by-side bar chart
# Side-by-side
ggplot(data = airline_tweets) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = airline, fill = airline_sentiment), 
           position = "dodge") + 
  labs(title = "Sentiment of Airline Tweets",
       x = "Airline",
       y = "Counts",
       fill = "Sentiment")

For side-by-side bar charts, it’s fairly difficult to assess marginal distributions; however, it is easy to assess conditional distributions. In particular, by making airline correspond to the x-axis, we can easily see the conditional distribution of airline_sentiment given each airline. To assess the marginal distribution of airline, we can look at the total area of the bars corresponding to each airline - while this isn’t ideal, I decided to make the above choice so we could at least easily see the conditional distribution.

  • A stacked bar chart
#stacked bar chart
ggplot(data = airline_tweets) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = airline, fill = airline_sentiment)) + 
  labs(title = "Sentiment of Airline Tweets",
       x = "Airline",
       y = "Counts",
       fill = "Sentiment")

For stacked bar charts, it’s especially easy to see the marginal distribution of the variable that corresponds to the height of the bars - thus, we made airline correspond to the height of the bars. Meanwhile, within each bar, we can now easily assess the conditional distribution of airline_sentiment given airline.

  • A mosaic plot (colored by Pearson residuals)
#mosaic plot
mosaicplot(table(airline_tweets$airline, airline_tweets$airline_sentiment),
           shade = TRUE,
           main = "Mosaic Plot of Airline and Sentiment")

For the mosaic plot, the width of the rectangles correspond to a marginal distribution, whereas the heights correspond to a conditional distribution. Thus, because the goal was to visualize the marginal distribution of airline (and the conditional distribution of airline_sentiment given airline), we ensured airline corresponded to the widths of the rectangles in the mosaic plot.

  • A facetted bar chart
#facetted bar chart
ggplot(data = airline_tweets) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = airline_sentiment, fill = airline_sentiment)) + 
  facet_grid(~ airline) + 
  labs(title = "Sentiment of Airline Tweets",
       x = "Airline",
       y = "Counts",
       fill = "Sentiment") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1))

Similar to side-by-side bar charts, it’s fairly difficult to assess marginal distributions for facetted bar charts; however, it is easy to assess conditional distributions. In particular, by making airline correspond to the facetting variable, we can easily see the conditional distribution of airline_sentiment given each airline. To assess the marginal distribution of airline, we can look at the total area of the bars in each facet - while this isn’t ideal, I decided to make the above choice so we could at least easily see the conditional distribution.

The faceted or side-by-side bar chart (which display essentially the same information) makes it easiest to see the conditional distribution of airline_sentiment given airline. Arguably, either the stacked bar chart, the side-by-side bar chart, or the faceted bar chart could strike the best balance between showing the marginal distribution of airline and the conditional distribution of airline_sentiment given airline. In the previous question, we stated that Delta, Southwest, and Virgin America appear to receive a larger proportion of positive tweets.
